\ copy = copy_term, reify = reify. Both dereference bound vars to their values
\ and recurse through pairs/arrays. copy mints fresh (shared) vars for unbound
\ ones; reify names them :_N canonically by first appearance.

\ copy dereferences bound vars to their values
lvar to A   lvar to B   [( 3 4 )] [( A B )] ~ drop   [( A B )] copy . cr     \ [( 3 4 )]

\ copy of a ground list is unchanged
[( 1 2 3 null )] copy . cr                                                   \ [( 1 2 3 null )]

\ copy preserves variable sharing (reify-of-copy canonicalises to reveal it)
lvar to X   [( X X null )] copy reify . cr                                   \ [( :_0 :_0 null )]

\ copy recurses into arrays and derefs
lvar to M   M 7 ~ drop   [ M ] copy 0 @i . cr                                \ 7

\ reify dereferences bound vars
lvar to P   lvar to Q   [( 5 6 )] [( P Q )] ~ drop   [( P Q )] reify . cr     \ [( 5 6 )]

\ reify names unbound vars :_N canonically, by first appearance, sharing kept
lvar to U   lvar to V   [( U V U null )] reify . cr                          \ [( :_0 :_1 :_0 null )]

\ a reified term is inert symbols, equal to the literal symbol list
lvar to W   [( W null )] reify   [( :_0 null )] = . cr                       \ 1

bye
